{"key":"post-11788453","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>11788453</id>\n<content>If you have agar, why use a syringe to inoculate the rye?&amp;nbsp; Simply use an agar wedge.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It sounds like your filters/lid combination isn't sealing properly.&amp;nbsp; Perhaps you've put the filters on the inside of the lid rather than on the outside?&amp;nbsp; Another common cause of bacterial infection is releasing the pressure after sterilizing rather than waiting for it to return to zero slowly.&amp;nbsp; You also shouldn't remove the jars until they're cool.&amp;nbsp; The old advice to 'remove while hot to shake' is based on using poor technique to prepare the rye.&amp;nbsp; Removing the jars while hot will lead to an increased rate of contamination because they draw in air as they cool and the contents shrink.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Also, 99% alcohol doesn't have the killing power of 70%.&amp;nbsp; That's why it's not recommended.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>11788509</next>\n<prev>11787934</prev>\n<first>11787934</first>\n<last>12482530</last>\n<when>1262967025</when>\n<utime>01/08/10 06:10 PM</utime>\n</post>"}